        {
            "block_label": "text",
            "block_content": "where $s^{\\prime}$ is the closed surface and $c$ is the per-unit-length capacitance desired. We have defined the closed contour around the perimeter of this surface as $c^{\\prime}$. The differential path length along this contour is denoted by $\\overrightarrow{dl^{\\prime}}$ and the normal to the surface is denoted as $\\overrightarrow{a_{n}^{\\prime}}$. Note that these surfaces and contours are designated with primes to distinguish them from the surfaces and contours used to determine the inductance above. Since the transverse electric field and electric flux density vector is from the upper conductor to the lower conductor, it is directed out of this closed surface $s^{\\prime}$ giving the enclosed",
